18d699ab [simon@midnightblue] is branch instruction on 6502 relative to the current instruction or the next one?
18d69a68 [deepseek-chat] #On the 6502 processor, branch instructions are relative to the next instruction, not the
18d69a68 [deepseek-chat] #current one.
18d69a68 [deepseek-chat] #
18d69a68 [deepseek-chat] #The branch offset is added to the program counter after it has already been incremented to
18d69a68 [deepseek-chat] #point to the next instruction. This means:
18d69a68 [deepseek-chat] #
18d69a68 [deepseek-chat] #- When a branch instruction is fetched, the PC points to the branch opcode
18d69a68 [deepseek-chat] #- The PC is incremented to point to the branch offset byte
18d69a68 [deepseek-chat] #- The PC is incremented again to point to the next instruction
18d69a68 [deepseek-chat] #- The offset is added to this PC value
18d69a68 [deepseek-chat] #
18d69a68 [deepseek-chat] #The offset is a signed 8-bit value (-128 to +127), so branches can jump:
18d69a68 [deepseek-chat] #- Forward up to 127 bytes
18d69a68 [deepseek-chat] #- Backward up to 128 bytes
18d69a68 [deepseek-chat] #
18d69a68 [deepseek-chat] #Example:
18d69a68 [deepseek-chat] #
18d69a68 [deepseek-chat] #BEQ $F0  ; Branch if equal to label
18d69a68 [deepseek-chat] #NOP      ; This is the "next instruction" the offset is relative to
18d69a68 [deepseek-chat] #
18d69a68 [deepseek-chat] #
18d69a68 [deepseek-chat] #This is why you sometimes see `$FE` (or -2) used to branch to the branch instruction itself,
18d69a68 [deepseek-chat] #creating an infinite loop.
18d69a68 [deepseek-chat] #
