18d767e9 [deepseek-chat] #
18d767e9 [deepseek-chat] #The version of Breakout that Steve Wozniak famously created for the Apple II was indeed
18d767e9 [deepseek-chat] #written in Integer BASIC.
18d767e9 [deepseek-chat] #
18d767e9 [deepseek-chat] #The confusion often arises because:
18d767e9 [deepseek-chat] #1.  The original arcade game "Breakout" by Atari (which Wozniak and Jobs worked on)
18d767e9 [deepseek-chat] #involved custom hardware.
18d767e9 [deepseek-chat] #2.  Wozniak's brilliant software version for the Apple II was a demo to show off the machine's
18d767e9 [deepseek-chat] #capabilities, and he wrote it in the BASIC interpreter he had designed.
18d767e9 [deepseek-chat] #
18d767e9 [deepseek-chat] #So, to be precise: The Apple II version of Breakout, written by Steve Wozniak, has its source
18d767e9 [deepseek-chat] #code in Integer BASIC.
