1a6bcb5a [kimi-k2.5] #Clever approach using PIO pin direction toggling to generate composite video levels with a passive
1a6bcb5a [kimi-k2.5] #resistor DAC.
1a6bcb5a [kimi-k2.5] #
1a6bcb5a [kimi-k2.5] #• Notable technique:* Using `in x,25` / `mov x,isr` to load large constants (>31) into
1a6bcb5a [kimi-k2.5] #registers. This shifts immediate values into the ISR then moves them to X, avoiding the 5-bit `set`
1a6bcb5a [kimi-k2.5] #limitation. This creates the cycle-count delays needed for PAL timing (64µs lines at 150MHz).
1a6bcb5a [kimi-k2.5] #
1a6bcb5a [kimi-k2.5] #• Circuit logic:*
1a6bcb5a [kimi-k2.5] #- Drive low = sync (0V)
1a6bcb5a [kimi-k2.5] #- Input/high-Z = black (biased by trimpot divider)
1a6bcb5a [kimi-k2.5] #- Drive high = white (via 330Ω/75Ω divider)
1a6bcb5a [kimi-k2.5] #
1a6bcb5b [kimi-k2.5] #• Issue:* `voltageTest()` is defined after main's return and unreachable. If you want to
1a6bcb5b [kimi-k2.5] #calibrate levels, move it before main or add a forward declaration and call it from main.
1a6bcb5b [kimi-k2.5] #
1a6bcb5b [kimi-k2.5] #• PIO observation:* The `vidblit` program runs autonomously without CPU intervention (no TX
1a6bcb5b [kimi-k2.5] #FIFO pushes), generating a fixed stripe pattern. If you want to output video data from RAM, you'll
1a6bcb5b [kimi-k2.5] #need to use `piosmput()` or autopull with a DMA channel feeding the FIFO.
1a6bcb5b [kimi-k2.5] #
1a6bcb5b [kimi-k2.5] #Ensure your `CMakeLists.txt` includes:
1a6bcb5b [kimi-k2.5] #
1a6bcb5b [kimi-k2.5] #pico_generate_pio_header(vidbit ${CMAKE_CURRENT_LIST_DIR}/vidblit.pio)
1a6bcb5b [kimi-k2.5] #
1a6bcb5b [kimi-k2.5] #
