1a7439da [gemini-3.1-pro] #Here are the answers to your questions regarding resetting and the BOOTSEL button:
1a7439da [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1a7439da [gemini-3.1-pro] #• 1. Where is `resetusbboot` declared?*
1a7439da [gemini-3.1-pro] #It is declared in `pico/bootrom.h`.
1a7439da [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1a7439da [gemini-3.1-pro] #• 2. Where is `ReadBootSel` declared?*
1a7439da [gemini-3.1-pro] #`ReadBootSel` is not a standard Pico SDK function. You are likely thinking of a custom community
1a7439da [gemini-3.1-pro] #function. The standard SDK method to read the BOOTSEL button is
1a7439da [gemini-3.1-pro] #`picoboardisbootsel_pressed()`, which requires `#include "pico/stdlib.h"`. Reading this
1a7439da [gemini-3.1-pro] #button is complex because it shares the QSPI Chip Select pin with the flash memory, so the
1a7439db [gemini-3.1-pro] #execution must temporarily pause flash access and run from RAM.
1a7439db [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1a7439db [gemini-3.1-pro] #• 3. `resetusbboot(0, 0)` does not stop the PIO*
1a7439db [gemini-3.1-pro] #When jumping to the bootrom, the CPU halts your program, but peripherals like the PIO may continue
1a7439db [gemini-3.1-pro] #running or holding their pin states. To ensure the PIO stops producing a video signal, you should
1a7439db [gemini-3.1-pro] #explicitly disable it and reset the peripheral block before rebooting.
1a7439db [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1a7439db [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1a7439db [gemini-3.1-pro] ##include "hardware/resets.h"
1a7439db [gemini-3.1-pro] ##include "pico/bootrom.h"
1a7439db [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1a7439db [gemini-3.1-pro] #void rebootToUsb() {
1a7439db [gemini-3.1-pro] #    // Disable state machine and reset the PIO0 hardware block
1a7439db [gemini-3.1-pro] #    pio_sm_set_enabled(pio0, VidStateMachine, false);
1a7439db [gemini-3.1-pro] #    reset_block(RESETS_RESET_PIO0_BITS);
1a7439db [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1a7439db [gemini-3.1-pro] #    reset_usb_boot(0, 0);
1a7439db [gemini-3.1-pro] #}
1a7439db [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1a7439db [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1a7439db [gemini-3.1-pro] #• 4. Simple way to have BOOTSEL held down cause reset using WDT*
1a7439db [gemini-3.1-pro] #You can poll the BOOTSEL button in your main loop and trigger a hardware watchdog reset. This will
1a7439db [gemini-3.1-pro] #restart your program normally (unlike `resetusbboot`, which mounts the Pico as a drive).
1a7439db [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1a7439dc [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1a7439dc [gemini-3.1-pro] ##include "hardware/watchdog.h"
1a7439dc [gemini-3.1-pro] #
