1a84db21 [simon@midnightblue] please explain support for stride skip in dma
1a84dbd8 [deepseek-chat] #The RP2350 DMA supports stride/skip through the `READADDR` and `WRITEADDR` reload
1a84dbd8 [deepseek-chat] #registers. This allows you to skip over memory when transferring non-contiguous data.
1a84dbd8 [deepseek-chat] #
1a84dbd8 [deepseek-chat] #• How it works:*
1a84dbd8 [deepseek-chat] #1. Primary transfer: Moves data from source to destination
1a84dbd8 [deepseek-chat] #2. Address reload: After each transfer, addresses jump by a stride value
1a84dbd8 [deepseek-chat] #3. Use case: Perfect for de-interlacing or accessing every Nth element
1a84dbd8 [deepseek-chat] #
1a84dbd8 [deepseek-chat] #• Key registers:*
1a84dbd8 [deepseek-chat] #- `READADDR` / `WRITEADDR`: Current transfer address
1a84dbd8 [deepseek-chat] #- `READADDRRELOAD` / `WRITEADDRRELOAD`: Value to reload after transfer completes
1a84dbd8 [deepseek-chat] #- Transfer count controls how many elements per "row"
1a84dbd9 [deepseek-chat] #
1a84dbd9 [deepseek-chat] #• Example: Skip every other line (interlaced extraction)*
1a84dbd9 [deepseek-chat] #
1a84dbd9 [deepseek-chat] #Memory: [Line0, Line1, Line2, Line3, Line4...]
1a84dbd9 [deepseek-chat] #Stride: 2 * line_size_words
1a84dbd9 [deepseek-chat] #Result: [Line0, Line2, Line4...] (odd field)
1a84dbd9 [deepseek-chat] #
1a84dbd9 [deepseek-chat] #
1a84dbd9 [deepseek-chat] #• Limitations on RP2350:*
1a84dbd9 [deepseek-chat] #- Stride is set via reload registers, not a dedicated stride register
1a84dbd9 [deepseek-chat] #- You need to calculate: `reloadaddr = currentaddr + stride`
1a84dbd9 [deepseek-chat] #- Works best with chaining for complex patterns
1a84dbd9 [deepseek-chat] #
1a84dbd9 [deepseek-chat] #• For your 39 words per line:*
1a84dbd9 [deepseek-chat] #- To extract odd lines: Stride = 78 words (2 lines)
1a84dbd9 [deepseek-chat] #- To extract even lines: Start at line 1, same stride
1a84dbd9 [deepseek-chat] #
1a84dbd9 [deepseek-chat] #• Alternative approach:*
1a84dbd9 [deepseek-chat] #Use two DMA channels with different starting addresses. Often simpler than stride
1a84dbd9 [deepseek-chat] #calculations.
1a84dbd9 [deepseek-chat] #
1a84dbd9 [deepseek-chat] #• Practical advice:*
1a84dbd9 [deepseek-chat] #For video interlacing, separate buffers (Option A) is usually cleaner than stride tricks. The DMA
1a84dbd9 [deepseek-chat] #can easily switch between two buffers without complex addressing math.
1a84dbd9 [deepseek-chat] #
1a84dbd9 [deepseek-chat] #Would you like the register-level details for implementing stride, or are you leaning toward the
1a84dbda [deepseek-chat] #two-buffer approach?
