1a84e7d0 [simon@midnightblue] is there a nature pal pixel clock frequency most digital tv will sample signal at?
1a84e884 [deepseek-chat] #Yes, there's a standard digital sampling frequency for PAL that modern digital TVs expect.
1a84e884 [deepseek-chat] #
1a84e884 [deepseek-chat] #• PAL Digital Sampling (ITU-R BT.601):*
1a84e884 [deepseek-chat] #- Luminance (Y) sampling: 13.5 MHz (common for both PAL and NTSC)
1a84e884 [deepseek-chat] #- Color difference (Cb/Cr): 6.75 MHz (4:2:2) or 3.375 MHz (4:2:0)
1a84e884 [deepseek-chat] #
1a84e884 [deepseek-chat] #• Why 13.5 MHz?*
1a84e884 [deepseek-chat] #- Derived from common multiple of PAL and NTSC line rates
1a84e884 [deepseek-chat] #- PAL: 625 lines × 15625 Hz = 13.5 MHz ÷ 864
1a84e884 [deepseek-chat] #- NTSC: 525 lines × 15734 Hz = 13.5 MHz ÷ 858
1a84e884 [deepseek-chat] #- Allows single digital standard for both systems
1a84e885 [deepseek-chat] #
1a84e885 [deepseek-chat] #• Your PIO clock at 150 MHz:*
1a84e885 [deepseek-chat] #- 150 MHz ÷ 13.5 MHz ≈ 11.111
1a84e885 [deepseek-chat] #- Not an integer ratio
1a84e885 [deepseek-chat] #- Common approach: Use 12 MHz (150 ÷ 12.5 = 12)
1a84e885 [deepseek-chat] #- Or 12.5 MHz (150 ÷ 12 = 12.5)
1a84e885 [deepseek-chat] #
1a84e885 [deepseek-chat] #• Practical considerations:*
1a84e885 [deepseek-chat] #1. TVs are tolerant - ±1000 ppm typical
1a84e885 [deepseek-chat] #2. Your current 9600 cycles/line:
1a84e885 [deepseek-chat] #   - 150 MHz ÷ 9600 = 15.625 kHz (PAL line rate)
1a84e885 [deepseek-chat] #   - Pixel clock: 150 MHz ÷ (9600/width) ≈ ?
1a84e885 [deepseek-chat] #3. For 1248 pixels active: 9600/1248 ≈ 7.69 cycles/pixel
1a84e885 [deepseek-chat] #
1a84e885 [deepseek-chat] #• Recommendation:*
1a84e885 [deepseek-chat] #Aim for 12-13 MHz pixel clock. Adjust your PIO timing to get close to 13.5 MHz if possible,
1a84e885 [deepseek-chat] #but 12 MHz will work with most TVs.
