1a8dd9fd [deepseek-chat] #Adding a PS/2 mouse/keyboard reader via PIO is a good approach. Here are key considerations:
1a8dd9fd [deepseek-chat] #
1a8dd9fd [deepseek-chat] #• PS/2 Protocol Basics:*
1a8dd9fd [deepseek-chat] #- Bidirectional serial protocol at 10-16.7 kHz
1a8dd9fd [deepseek-chat] #- Data on single pin with clock on separate pin
1a8dd9fd [deepseek-chat] #- 11-bit frames: start(0), 8 data bits, parity, stop(1)
1a8dd9fd [deepseek-chat] #- Open-collector signaling requires pull-ups
1a8dd9fd [deepseek-chat] #
1a8dd9fd [deepseek-chat] #• PIO Design Choices:*
1a8dd9fd [deepseek-chat] #
1a8dd9fd [deepseek-chat] #1. Pin Configuration:
1a8dd9fd [deepseek-chat] #   - Need 2 pins per device (data, clock)
1a8dd9fd [deepseek-chat] #   - Typically GPIO pull-ups enabled
1a8dd9fd [deepseek-chat] #   - Consider interrupt handling for clock edges
1a8dd9fd [deepseek-chat] #
1a8dd9fd [deepseek-chat] #2. State Machine Approach:
1a8dd9fd [deepseek-chat] #   - Could use one SM per PS/2 device
1a8dd9fd [deepseek-chat] #   - Clock pin as SET/input for synchronization
1a8dd9fd [deepseek-chat] #   - Data pin sampled on clock falling edges
1a8dd9fd [deepseek-chat] #
1a8dd9fd [deepseek-chat] #3. Timing Constraints:
1a8dd9fe [deepseek-chat] #   - PS/2 clock ~10-16.7 µs period
1a8dd9fe [deepseek-chat] #   - PIO at 150MHz gives ~1500 cycles per bit - plenty of margin
1a8dd9fe [deepseek-chat] #   - Need debouncing (software or PIO delay)
1a8dd9fe [deepseek-chat] #
1a8dd9fe [deepseek-chat] #4. Data Handling:
1a8dd9fe [deepseek-chat] #   - PIO can shift in 11-bit frames
1a8dd9fe [deepseek-chat] #   - Parity checking optional (often skipped)
1a8dd9fe [deepseek-chat] #   - Need FIFO for key/mouse codes
1a8dd9fe [deepseek-chat] #   - Multi-byte sequences for mouse movement
1a8dd9fe [deepseek-chat] #
1a8dd9fe [deepseek-chat] #5. Bidirectional Considerations:
1a8dd9fe [deepseek-chat] #   - Host can send commands (LED control, reset)
1a8dd9fe [deepseek-chat] #   - Requires switching data pin direction
1a8dd9fe [deepseek-chat] #   - May need separate TX/RX state machines
1a8dd9fe [deepseek-chat] #
1a8dd9fe [deepseek-chat] #• Simplified Approach:*
1a8dd9fe [deepseek-chat] #Start with read-only implementation for keyboard, then add:
1a8dd9fe [deepseek-chat] #- Mouse support (3-byte packets)
1a8dd9fe [deepseek-chat] #- Command capability
1a8dd9fe [deepseek-chat] #- Error recovery (timeouts, resync)
1a8dd9fe [deepseek-chat] #
1a8dd9fe [deepseek-chat] #• Integration:*
1a8dd9fe [deepseek-chat] #- Share PIO with video/audio or use separate PIO block
1a8dd9fe [deepseek-chat] #- Interrupt on data ready vs polling
1a8dd9fe [deepseek-chat] #- Queue for keycodes in main loop
1a8dd9ff [deepseek-chat] #
1a8dd9ff [deepseek-chat] #The PIO can reliably handle the timing-critical bit sampling, leaving protocol decoding to the CPU.
