1a8dea9f [simon@midnightblue] does the ps/2 protocol have a correct name?
1a8deb31 [deepseek-chat] #Yes, the PS/2 protocol is properly called the "PS/2 interface" or "PS/2 connector
1a8deb31 [deepseek-chat] #protocol".
1a8deb31 [deepseek-chat] #
1a8deb31 [deepseek-chat] #• Technical Standards:*
1a8deb31 [deepseek-chat] #- Originally defined by IBM in 1987 for the IBM Personal System/2 computers
1a8deb31 [deepseek-chat] #- Standardized in IBM Technical Reference manuals
1a8deb31 [deepseek-chat] #- Sometimes referred to as "AT keyboard interface" (the predecessor)
1a8deb31 [deepseek-chat] #- The physical connector is officially "6-pin mini-DIN"
1a8deb31 [deepseek-chat] #
1a8deb31 [deepseek-chat] #• Protocol Details:*
1a8deb31 [deepseek-chat] #- Bidirectional serial protocol
1a8deb31 [deepseek-chat] #- Clock typically driven by the device (keyboard/mouse)
1a8deb31 [deepseek-chat] #- Often called "PS/2 communication protocol"
1a8deb31 [deepseek-chat] #- Not to be confused with the PS/2 mouse port which uses the same connector but different data
1a8deb31 [deepseek-chat] #format
1a8deb31 [deepseek-chat] #
1a8deb31 [deepseek-chat] #• In Documentation:*
1a8deb31 [deepseek-chat] #You'll typically see:
1a8deb32 [deepseek-chat] #- "PS/2 keyboard interface"
1a8deb32 [deepseek-chat] #- "PS/2 mouse protocol"
1a8deb32 [deepseek-chat] #- "PS/2 device communication"
1a8deb32 [deepseek-chat] #
1a8deb32 [deepseek-chat] #While "PS/2 protocol" is commonly understood, the more precise term is "PS/2 interface
1a8deb32 [deepseek-chat] #protocol" when referring to the electrical and data communication specification.
1a8deb32 [deepseek-chat] #
