1a8dfe53 [simon@midnightblue] both pins are inputs?
1a8dff1d [deepseek-chat] #For a PS/2 keyboard/mouse (device-to-host communication), both pins should be
1a8dff1d [deepseek-chat] #inputs on the RP2350 side.
1a8dff1d [deepseek-chat] #
1a8dff1d [deepseek-chat] #• Correct Configuration:*
1a8dff1d [deepseek-chat] #- GP0 (Data): Input with pull-up
1a8dff1d [deepseek-chat] #- GP1 (Clock): Input with pull-up
1a8dff1d [deepseek-chat] #
1a8dff1d [deepseek-chat] #• Why:*
1a8dff1d [deepseek-chat] #1. PS/2 protocol: The keyboard/mouse generates both clock and data signals
1a8dff1d [deepseek-chat] #2. Open-collector: Devices pull lines low, release to high (pull-ups provide high state)
1a8dff1d [deepseek-chat] #3. Host role: Your RP2350 is the host - it listens, doesn't drive these lines during normal
1a8dff1d [deepseek-chat] #operation
1a8dff1d [deepseek-chat] #
1a8dff1e [deepseek-chat] #• Exception - Host to Device:*
1a8dff1e [deepseek-chat] #If you need to send commands to the device (LED control, reset), you'd temporarily:
1a8dff1e [deepseek-chat] #1. Pull Clock low for 100µs
1a8dff1e [deepseek-chat] #2. Pull Data low (start bit)
1a8dff1e [deepseek-chat] #3. Release Clock
1a8dff1e [deepseek-chat] #4. Send bits with Clock/Data toggling
1a8dff1e [deepseek-chat] #5. Return both to inputs when done
1a8dff1e [deepseek-chat] #
1a8dff1e [deepseek-chat] #But for basic keycode reading, both pins remain inputs with pull-ups enabled.
1a8dff1e [deepseek-chat] #
1a8dff1e [deepseek-chat] #• Setup:*
1a8dff1e [deepseek-chat] #
1a8dff1e [deepseek-chat] #gpio_init(0); gpio_init(1);
1a8dff1e [deepseek-chat] #gpio_set_dir(0, GPIO_IN); gpio_set_dir(1, GPIO_IN);
1a8dff1e [deepseek-chat] #gpio_pull_up(0); gpio_pull_up(1);
1a8dff1e [deepseek-chat] #
1a8dff1e [deepseek-chat] #
1a8dff1e [deepseek-chat] #This matches your "dedicated state machine no interrupts" approach - PIO monitors these input pins.
1a8dff1e [deepseek-chat] #
