1a8e0033 [simon@midnightblue] both need shmitt option?
1a8e00d4 [deepseek-chat] #Yes, both pins should have Schmitt triggers enabled for PS/2.
1a8e00d4 [deepseek-chat] #
1a8e00d4 [deepseek-chat] #• Why both:*
1a8e00d4 [deepseek-chat] #1. Clock line: Critical for clean edge detection - PS/2 devices generate the clock with
1a8e00d4 [deepseek-chat] #open-collector
1a8e00d4 [deepseek-chat] #2. Data line: Also open-collector, benefits from hysteresis for noise immunity
1a8e00d4 [deepseek-chat] #3. Signal quality: PS/2 signals can have slow rise times (pull-up dependent)
1a8e00d4 [deepseek-chat] #
1a8e00d4 [deepseek-chat] #• RP2350 Setup:*
1a8e00d4 [deepseek-chat] #
1a8e00d4 [deepseek-chat] #gpio_set_input_hysteresis_enabled(0, true);  // Data
1a8e00d5 [deepseek-chat] #gpio_set_input_hysteresis_enabled(1, true);  // Clock
1a8e00d5 [deepseek-chat] #
1a8e00d5 [deepseek-chat] #
1a8e00d5 [deepseek-chat] #• Default State:*
1a8e00d5 [deepseek-chat] #On RP2350/Pico, Schmitt triggers are usually enabled by default on most GPIOs, but explicitly
1a8e00d5 [deepseek-chat] #enabling ensures:
1a8e00d5 [deepseek-chat] #- Consistent behavior across all pins
1a8e00d5 [deepseek-chat] #- Clear documentation in code
1a8e00d5 [deepseek-chat] #- Portability if code reused
1a8e00d5 [deepseek-chat] #
1a8e00d5 [deepseek-chat] #• Note:* Schmitt triggers consume slightly more power, but for just two pins this is
1a8e00d5 [deepseek-chat] #negligible.
1a8e00d5 [deepseek-chat] #
1a8e00d5 [deepseek-chat] #Given PS/2's relatively low speed (10-16.7 kHz) and open-collector signaling, the hysteresis
1a8e00d5 [deepseek-chat] #provides valuable noise margin for reliable operation.
1a8e00d5 [deepseek-chat] #
