1a8ee24b [gemini-3.1-pro] #Hello!
1a8ee24b [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1a8ee24b [gemini-3.1-pro] #To answer your question: Yes, a standard PS/2 keyboard should work without any fuss. Keyboards
1a8ee24b [gemini-3.1-pro] #automatically send a self-test passed byte (`0xAA`) on power-up and will immediately transmit
1a8ee24c [gemini-3.1-pro] #scancodes whenever a key is pressed.
1a8ee24c [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1a8ee24c [gemini-3.1-pro] #A PS/2 mouse, however, will not send data automatically. While it also sends the initial `0xAA`
1a8ee24c [gemini-3.1-pro] #byte on power-up, it requires the host to explicitly send an "Enable Data Reporting" command
1a8ee24c [gemini-3.1-pro] #(`0xF4`) before it will begin transmitting movement and button packets.
1a8ee24c [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1a8ee24c [gemini-3.1-pro] #Because your current PIO implementation only handles device-to-host (RX) communication, the mouse
1a8ee24c [gemini-3.1-pro] #remains idle because it never receives the command to start sending data. To support a mouse, you
1a8ee24c [gemini-3.1-pro] #will need to implement host-to-device (TX) communication to send that initialization command.
1a8ee24c [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1a8ee24c [gemini-3.1-pro] #As a quick hardware note: PS/2 devices generally require a 5V power supply to operate. Since the
1a8ee24c [gemini-3.1-pro] #RP2350 is a 3.3V device, ensure the devices are powered by 5V but that the data and clock lines are
1a8ee24c [gemini-3.1-pro] #operating as open-collector and are only being pulled up to 3.3V to protect your GPIO pins.
1a8ee24c [gemini-3.1-pro] #
