1a8f277a [gemini-3.1-pro] #• 2. Powering the PS/2 connector from VSYS*
1a8f277a [gemini-3.1-pro] #Using VSYS (typically ~5V if powered via USB) is correct for providing power, as standard PS/2
1a8f277a [gemini-3.1-pro] #devices require 5V. However, please be cautious: RP2350 GPIO pins operate at 3.3V and are
1a8f277a [gemini-3.1-pro] #not 5V tolerant. PS/2 devices pull the Clock and Data lines high to their supply voltage.
1a8f277a [gemini-3.1-pro] #If they pull those lines up to 5V, it can damage the RP2350. You should use logic level shifters on
1a8f277a [gemini-3.1-pro] #the Clock and Data lines to safely bridge the 5V device to the 3.3V microcontroller.
1a8f277a [gemini-3.1-pro] #
1a8f277a [gemini-3.1-pro] #• 3. How many PIO can I have on RP2350?*
1a8f277a [gemini-3.1-pro] #The RP2350 contains 3 independent PIO blocks (PIO0, PIO1, and PIO2). Each block contains 4
1a8f277a [gemini-3.1-pro] #state machines, giving you a total of 12 state machines to work with. Your current code
1a8f277a [gemini-3.1-pro] #correctly initializes all three blocks.
